{"title":"End-to-end Contrastive Language-Speech Pretraining Model For Long-form Spoken Question Answering","domain":"SPEECH","seeds":[{"problem":"Long-form spoken question answering requires retrieving question-relevant segments from lengthy audio, but existing end-to-end speech-text retrievers perform poorly and direct speech–text alignment suffers from a large modality gap; pipeline ASR→text-retrieval can be accurate but is slower and error-prone.","method":"CLSR is an end-to-end contrastive language–speech retriever that first converts acoustic features into text-like token representations, then aligns them in text space. It uses a non-autoregressive Paraformer with CIF to map frames to token steps and produces token distributions, followed by a vector-quantizer adaptor that yields one-hot-like tokens. These are projected into a frozen text encoder’s (BGE) embedding space, and sentence-level [CLS] embeddings are aligned with queries via symmetric InfoNCE. Joint training combines ASR losses (CE, MAE for CIF, MWER) with contrastive loss, yielding strong retrieval on Spoken-SQuAD*, LibriSQA, SLUE-SQA-5, and DRCD, outperforming E2E baselines (CLAP, SpeechDPR) and matching or surpassing Whisper+BGE on several datasets."},{"problem":"Training the non-autoregressive ASR within the retriever is brittle—recognition errors degrade the learned token distributions and downstream retrieval quality; improving the decoder’s context modeling and stability is needed.","method":"CLSR introduces a sampler for training: after a first-pass decode, it compares predicted tokens with ground truth, and selectively replaces embeddings of misrecognized tokens by their true text embeddings at a mixing ratio λ to form semantic features for a second decoding pass. This stabilizes token distributions used by the VQ adaptor and improves both WER and retrieval recall. Ablations show that removing the VQ quantizer severely harms retrieval, while enabling the sampler improves ASR and retrieval metrics (e.g., on Spoken-SQuAD, WER decreases and R@k increases)."},{"problem":"Feeding entire long audio to large audio language models (LALMs) is slow and harms answer quality due to irrelevant content.","method":"CLSR is used as a speech retriever in a speech-RAG pipeline: long audio is segmented (e.g., 40 s windows), CLSR ranks segments by similarity to the question, and only the top segment is sent to a LALM (Qwen-Audio). On modified SLUE-SQA-5 with ~30-minute documents, this improves EM from 18.00 to 27.60 and F1 from 23.55 to 35.10, while reducing inference time by ~10×, demonstrating practical gains in both accuracy and latency for long-form SQA."}]}
